stylometry: @risk first allows you to run the same simulation several times simultaneously using a different value of some key input.  So what this @risk is doing is running different values for that key input to come up with solution.  For example, you have baseball bats that sell for 100, 150 ,200, 250, and 300 dollars. The @risk will try all inputs simultaneously by running 5 simulations of 1,000 iterations each with random demands.  In this simulation model it can specify any cell or range of output cells.  After the simulation is ran it can create graphs based on values to see trends and forecasts.
